[2026-03-18T11:37:58.906Z] [STDOUT] {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_014wSrafnTQqLBsXhJmQy7zT","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_017gDgttwab9vvZQv5YvTGmQ","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"curl -s -X POST http://localhost:3000/api/ideas \\\n  -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n  -d '{\n    \"scan_id\": \"14c00316-3fb2-4961-af16-5eb0c15f6f99\",\n    \"project_id\": \"c6fd0474-19f1-4223-b6a9-752077c51d3d\",\n    \"scan_type\": \"moonshot_architect\",\n    \"category\": \"functionality\",\n    \"title\": \"Adaptive Self-Tuning Trigger Intelligence\",\n    \"description\": \"Build an execution-history-aware trigger optimizer that learns optimal firing schedules from past outcomes. Instead of static cron expressions, triggers gain an adaptive mode where the system analyzes execution success rates, durations, costs, and output quality across time windows to automatically shift trigger timing. For example, a persona monitoring a git repo learns that commits cluster between 10am-2pm and shifts its polling trigger accordingly. Implementation: add a trigger_history table tracking fire-time vs outcome metrics, and a computeAdaptiveNextTriggerAt function using exponential moving averages. First sprint: instrument triggerSchedulerTick to record outcome correlations in a new trigger_metrics table.\",\n    \"reasoning\": \"The 5-second fixed tick evaluating rigid cron expressions wastes compute on low-value executions and misses optimal windows. Self-tuning triggers would reduce wasted Claude API spend by skipping low-probability windows while catching high-value moments. No competitor offers AI-agent scheduling that learns from its own execution history - this would be a signature capability users describe as magical.\",\n    \"effort\": 8,\n    \"impact\": 9,\n    \"risk\": 6\n  }'","description":"Save idea 2 without context_id"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":nu